1

00:00:00,050  -->  00:00:03,990
How should we work with these outliers in practice?

2

00:00:03,990  -->  00:00:05,565
At the very least,

3

00:00:05,565  -->  00:00:07,385
we should note that they exist.

4

00:00:07,385  -->  00:00:11,940
We need to realize the impact they have on our summary statistics.

5

00:00:11,940  -->  00:00:16,835
In this case, greatly increasing our mean and our standard deviation.

6

00:00:16,835  -->  00:00:20,705
If the outliers are typos or data entry errors,

7

00:00:20,705  -->  00:00:23,105
this is a reason to remove these points.

8

00:00:23,105  -->  00:00:25,205
Or if we know what they should be,

9

00:00:25,205  -->  00:00:28,370
we could change them with the correct values.

10

00:00:28,370  -->  00:00:30,380
In cases like the example above,

11

00:00:30,380  -->  00:00:32,120
we might try to understand,

12

00:00:32,120  -->  00:00:36,530
what was so different about the outlier when compared to the other individuals?

13

00:00:36,530  -->  00:00:39,770
How did this entrepreneur become so successful?

14

00:00:39,770  -->  00:00:43,665
And why are the earnings so large in comparison?

15

00:00:43,665  -->  00:00:48,730
There is an entire field aimed at this idea called the anomaly detection.

16

00:00:48,730  -->  00:00:53,210
You will notice measures associated with the five number summary, like the minimum,

17

00:00:53,210  -->  00:00:56,060
the maximum and the quartiles one, two,

18

00:00:56,060  -->  00:00:59,770
three, are more informative when outliers are present.

19

00:00:59,770  -->  00:01:04,550
This example shows that you need to be careful about how we share our results and

20

00:01:04,550  -->  00:01:09,980
state our conclusions using summary statistics when we have outliers.

21

00:01:09,980  -->  00:01:15,625
A single number can be very misleading about what is actually happening in our data.

22

00:01:15,625  -->  00:01:19,420
Some statistics are more misleading than others.

23

00:01:19,420  -->  00:01:22,955
If you are the consumer of information based on data,

24

00:01:22,955  -->  00:01:24,510
which we all are,

25

00:01:24,510  -->  00:01:26,480
it's important to know how to ask

26

00:01:26,480  -->  00:01:30,680
the right questions regarding the statistics around you.
